Let's summarize the previous, the fiftieth week.
A total of three thousand one hundred and sixty-two cases were added, which has increased by eight point two percent compared to the previous week in absolute numbers.
Here we can add that if we take testing, then almost one, almost twelve percent of these positive tests, positive tests are so-called tenth day tests, that is, when close contacts can take a test on the tenth day, then we see and reflect a quite large number of patients, which is very positive.
And the incidence is still on the rise in ten counties, especially in Harju County, Jõgeva County, Järva County, Lääne-Viru County, Ida-Viru County, Pärnu County, Rapla County.
Currently, we see a trend that the incidence from the north is starting to decline downwards, towards the south, which means that it is moving from Ida-Viru County towards Tartu County, towards Võru County, which actually also creates a cautious attitude towards these counties.
In terms of infection sites, nothing has changed pattern-wise, people are more likely to get infected within the family, at work, there are also other places of infection, as a result of which certain restrictions and limitations were imposed by the Government.
What continues to be a concern for us is how many of these cases we do not know about the infection.
This number was thirty-four percent last week, which again indicates that we still have a high risk of infection and the disease can be caught from anywhere.
We continue to register imported cases of disease, but fortunately this number is decreasing week by week and last week there were sixty-one.
And most of these cases come to us from Russia, Finland-Sweden, and Sweden.
Age structure.
As the number of cases is increasing rapidly, there are more cases in all age groups.
Mostly, more cases were added in the age group of sixty to sixty-nine.
There were seventeen percent of them, fifty to fifty-nine thirteen and forty to forty-nine twelve percent.
The positive moment is that last week the number of sick people aged ninety plus decreased by a quarter.
We know that Covid disease occurs both with and without symptoms, so last week the proportion of patients without symptoms was ten percent.
And one hundred and eighty-seven people needed hospitalization.
It is very important that almost eighty percent of those hospitalized were aged sixty plus, which suggests that the disease is worsening and the course of the disease will be more serious in older people.
We continue to be concerned about care institutions which are the most vulnerable risk areas and we did a small analysis, if we compared the fourteen-day incidence per one hundred thousand inhabitants, both in nursing homes and among the general population, then among the sixty plus clients staying in nursing homes, the risk of infection is almost seven times higher.
So again, if the disease gets into nursing homes, it is a serious problem.
And of course, we continue to repeat that our healthcare system is currently under a lot of strain.
And we have to do everything to ensure that all people who need hospital treatment, not only Covid patients, but also people coming to the hospital with other problems, get the treatment they need.
A few words about the incidence in Harju County.
As of today, the fourteen-day incidence per one hundred thousand inhabitants was five hundred and fifty-eight point eighty-two.
The number for Tallinn was five hundred and ninety, in Loksa city one thousand three hundred and thirty-eight, in Maardu city seven hundred and fifty-one.
"But let's compare this to Ida-Virumaa, where the figure is one thousand fifty-three, so Ida-Virumaa is currently our biggest concern. In Harju County, nearly seventeen thousand people are actively monitored, of which fourteen thousand are close contacts and over three thousand are active cases, and today we have twenty-four active outbreaks, which are mostly at work, workplaces, family clusters but also in nursing homes. And now, what should we do next, how should we behave? To put it simply, in order for us to overcome this crisis, everything is very simple and clear. Everyone who is sick should calmly go through the illness at home and all the sick during the time they are infectious should minimize their contact. Then we can get rid of the virus. Well, this is an ideal world, towards which we are moving. But certainly, we probably cannot achieve this one hundred percent. But still, we all need to contribute together now to not spread the virus and help those who need help. And what we should continue to do, we should adhere to the measures established in the country, we should keep distance, wear masks, reduce contacts, avoid crowded places and events, skip big parties this time. And we should spend Christmas mostly at home and in a narrow family circle and with those people with whom we communicate daily and stay at home as much as possible and enjoy the beautiful Estonian nature, to reduce the risk of getting infected and not to pass the infection on to anyone in the family. I wish everyone a beautiful Christmas mood and stay healthy, thank you! Thank you, Dr. Irina Dontšenko and the corona virus from the perspective of Tallinn Mayor Mihhail Kõlvart. Hello from me too, based on the epidemiological situation, as of this week, high school students continue to study remotely, primary school students also study remotely, but the study content is mainly creative tasks and also creative learning."
As announced at the end of last week, Tallinn municipal schools also offer primary school students the opportunity to use the extended day group service in the morning. According to today's data, this service is used by an average of three hundred children across Tallinn, so there is a need for it. Distance learning is also in place in Tallinn municipal hobby schools. This means that most of the activities take place remotely or not at all. But face-to-face lessons are held one-on-one, which is also allowed. And the situation in Tallinn kindergartens is currently such that about fifty groups are in isolation or quarantine. Similarly, forty-three employees. Parallel to today's organization of teaching, schools are also preparing for January based on different scenarios. The Education Department is mapping the situation and preparing the necessary resources in case we have to start distance learning in January. Of course, we hope that such a need will not arise, but we must be prepared for it. And we have once again discussed the situation with our representatives in the field of education, including school and municipal school directors, representatives in the social field, but also with our hospital leaders. We try to keep the situation under control, but at the same time we also think about what else needs to be prepared in case the situation worsens. And from the city side, we continue to appeal to citizens to keep their distance and wear a mask at outdoor events, despite the fact that there is no legal obligation to do so. But it would be quite sensible if we want at least this opportunity to remain for us for Christmas, so that the city could organize these outdoor events. So once again a big request, it only depends on us how the situation will develop. There is no need to wait for stricter regulations from the state, from the city, because the rules are meant to protect us. And we can follow these rules independently and behave accordingly without anyone watching, controlling and punishing.
