Christmas and the end of the year are fast approaching, then there will be fireworks at the end of the year and other suitable activities. And we have words of caution today from both the mayor and the representative of the Animal Protection Society. Mayor Mihhail Kõlvart. Yes, fireworks have traditionally been a symbol of the New Year. The city has also organized this every year and this year this event may have a special meaning. First of all, we all need positive emotions, which have been scarce lately. And the city has tried to provide this emotion in the urban space. However, we must take into account the current epidemiological situation. Therefore, of course, such a traditional event will not take place in Freedom Square. And we want to disperse people. So this year, fireworks will take place in different places, in different districts, almost in every district, except Nõmme and Kristiine. Six places have been chosen where fireworks will take place. And once again we turn to the citizens, if we want these events to take place, if we want the city to organize fireworks, then we need to keep a distance and also wear a mask. At the same time, the places have been chosen so that this would be possible. But we have another very important appeal to the people of Tallinn. That we organize fireworks centrally in different places, hoping that people will not start organizing it privately, will not start buying, and will not start firing. Because this is a problem for both people and animals.
And this is an annual problem and we need to understand that it is not environmentally friendly either. And we really hope that this understanding will develop more widely among our people this year. That there are specialists who can do this professionally and that's exactly why we do it, but all private fireworks should be cancelled, we try to protect each other, but also our smaller friends and I would gladly pass the word to the representative of the Animal Protection Society. Thank you, Mr. Mayor. Yes, the press conference is attended by Kaisa Kamm, the head of direct assistance of the Estonian Animal Protection Society, so the joyful New Year's Eve is a bit of a worry for you. Please. Hello from the Estonian Animal Protection Society. And I am first of all very pleased that the more the year progresses, the more we talk about the negative impact of fireworks on both animals and the environment. Here also a big thank you to Tallinn, which is now organizing such a safe environment for fireworks and I hope that this will not remain a one-year venture and other cities and municipalities will follow this example. The reason why the Estonian Animal Protection Society is so concerned about these fireworks is several. First of all, these are not just the concerns of our domestic animals, dogs and cats, but also the general urban animals, there are also horses, birds. But I think I would first like to talk about our domestic animals. Fireworks cause a lot of distress to them because it is loud and it causes irrational fear in dogs. They don't know how to behave, they start to flee, freeze, I believe that if someone manages to research, then the statistics of the Tallinn animal shelter, then there are very many running dogs, it can cause accidents. Plus just worry. In addition, there are our birds in the city. They either fly very far, they can't get back, food supplies run out. We simply cause a lot of suffering to them without any reason.
Therefore, it would be very good if you would simply go to places that are controlled, we know where these are happening. Pet owners can monitor where these fireworks are taking place and we don't have to fear that when they go outside with their dog, indiscriminate fireworks will occur. This is one of our main concerns. Thank you! And probably from here we can still add and ask that if at all possible, parents should also keep an eye on their little ones and not necessarily have to set off their own, self-initiated fireworks on Christmas Eve and the first day of Christmas. So maybe we could somehow get rid of this custom. But here probably parental care and teaching is needed, what fits and what does not. But thank you anyway, Kaisa Kamm, the head of direct assistance of the Estonian Animal Protection Society. Dear journalists, do you have any questions for our press conference participants? I don't see any questions, but Mr. Mayor, today we are planning to have our last gathering of the year in this press conference room. We never rule out the possibility that there may be a need for an unplanned post-session press conference or other gathering. But today we are here for the last time this year, because next week the city government will be holding a meeting in the town hall. We hope that the corona situation will allow it. Yes, thank you, indeed, the beautiful Christmas time and New Year are approaching. There is also a traditional desire to look back, draw conclusions and share plans for the next year. But what I want to confirm on behalf of the city, the city government, is that our daily work does not stop during the holidays. There is a special need for this today, as the situation needs to be constantly monitored and operational decisions need to be made if necessary. Especially considering the current situation. But we are ready to do this every day. I think we know what we need to do.
Yes, and regardless of how the situation will develop, we can assure from the city's side that we are prepared for various scenarios, we are ready to support and assist the citizens if necessary and we also have the confidence that we will manage in any case.
And I believe that this faith is not just an emotion.
This faith is also a very strong energy and energetics that we have.
Because we know what we need to do, we are ready to act and we hope and call on our people, the people of Tallinn and all the people of Estonia to approach the current situation in the same way.
Yes, it is not good, it is difficult.
